SIMPLE: sapphire
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sapphire
<hw>Sap"phire</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>saphir</ets>, F. <ets>saphir</ets>, L. <ets>sapphirus</ets>, Gr.
<?/, of Oriental origin; cf. Heb. <ets>sapp⟦imac⟧r</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Native alumina or aluminium
sesquioxide, <chform>Al2O3</chform>; corundum; esp., the blue
transparent variety of corundum, highly prized as a gem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of rubies, <qex>sapphires</qex>, and of pearl⟦eacute⟧s white.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sapphire</xex> occurs in hexagonal crystals and
also in granular and massive forms. The name <xex>sapphire</xex> is
usually restricted to the blue crystals, while the bright red crystals
are called <xex>Oriental rubies</xex> (see under <er>Ruby</er>), the
amethystine variety <xex>Oriental amethyst</xex> (see under
<er>Amethyst</er>), and the dull massive varieties <xex>corundum</xex>
(a name which is also used as a general term to include all varieties).
See <er>Corundum</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The color of the gem; bright blue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any humming bird of the genus
<gen>Hylocharis</gen>, native of South America. The throat and breast
are usually bright blue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Star sapphire</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Asteriated sapphire</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a
kind of sapphire which exhibits asterism.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sapphire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sapphire
<hw>Sap"phire</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or resembling sapphire;
sapphirine; blue.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>sapphire</xex> blaze.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sapphirine</ent>⟦br⟧
